Then the next day she said, look, all right, I'll tell you what.

35:58.647 --> 36:00.009
Go over to my friend.

36:00.089 --> 36:01.731
She'll introduce you.

36:01.751 --> 36:03.493
And then I met another person.

36:03.694 --> 36:04.515
Can you nail this down?

36:04.575 --> 36:06.658
When exactly this was for me?

36:06.958 --> 36:08.500
Well, the show came out in 1983.

36:10.022 --> 36:12.345
And it's still talked about.

36:12.625 --> 36:16.190
And how long did it take you to... I'm just going to check the timer.

36:16.951 --> 36:17.372
To write.

36:17.732 --> 36:19.374
To do the work, not just to write.

36:19.935 --> 36:20.696
Oh, about six months.

36:23.059 --> 36:27.064
But it was the biggest lesson in my life because... And it was called Widows.

36:27.184 --> 36:27.625
Widows.

36:28.465 --> 36:36.897
And what happened, because it was such a success in England, it was bought outright by Disney Studios.

36:37.919 --> 36:39.541
And they brought me over.

36:40.062 --> 36:41.083
Here.

36:41.103 --> 36:42.926
To Hollywood.

36:42.946 --> 36:50.156
And so there you've got, I mean, it's difficult to imagine, but you've got an actress that hankered after Hollywood.

36:50.176 --> 36:51.959
All her career as an actress.

36:51.979 --> 36:57.086
And suddenly I am first class in the Beverly Hills.

36:57.627 --> 36:58.168
And I mean,

36:58.368 --> 36:58.989
As a writer?

36:59.450 --> 37:00.211
As a writer.

37:00.551 --> 37:03.977
I've got the roses, I've got the fruit, the champagne.

37:04.718 --> 37:09.565
And I think, it was like magic time.

37:10.306 --> 37:11.608
And I was so dumb.

37:12.329 --> 37:14.172
I had no idea what the hell was going on.

37:14.192 --> 37:17.137
They kept ringing up and saying, oh, your car isn't coming for you today.

37:17.157 --> 37:18.959
I said, that's okay, because I was by the pool.

37:19.680 --> 37:21.423
Paid holiday.

37:21.443 --> 37:24.628
And then eventually I went to see Katzenberg at Disney.

37:26.077 --> 37:28.881
You were brought over to do new stuff, right?

37:28.921 --> 37:33.809
They wanted me to do the movie of Widows, in Hollywood.

37:33.829 --> 37:34.810
And was it produced?

37:35.391 --> 37:42.102
No, because when I got there, I discovered this extraordinary thing.

37:42.142 --> 37:48.652
They had bought this, but nobody had read it, and nobody had looked at the video.

37:50.294 --> 37:53.940
And so I went in to

37:54.410 --> 37:56.292
talk to the heads of the studio.

37:57.393 --> 38:00.396
And they said to me, would you pitch it?

38:02.218 --> 38:02.978
I said, pitch what?

38:04.440 --> 38:05.661
I said, I've been here three days.

38:05.721 --> 38:07.463
They said, would you pitch Widows?

38:08.243 --> 38:09.745
I said, well, haven't you read it?

38:10.606 --> 38:15.551
I couldn't believe that they'd outbidded every single studio.

38:15.971 --> 38:18.093
But that's what I understand about them.

38:18.794 --> 38:20.756
So I said, oh, so you want the story?

38:21.396 --> 38:22.257
So they said, yes.

38:23.080 --> 38:27.886
So because I'd never done a pitch before, I thought they wanted the whole story.

38:27.906 --> 38:30.749
So I reenacted the six hours.

38:31.831 --> 38:35.295
They were sitting there and kind of... In a stupor, huh?

38:35.535 --> 38:38.379
In a stupor, and I said, and then she comes and she gets by the door.

38:38.799 --> 38:39.701
I did the deaths.

38:40.762 --> 38:42.104
Well, you learned something, didn't you?

38:42.304 --> 38:47.831
And at the end of it, Jeffrey Katzenberg said to me, where are the laughs?

38:48.732 --> 38:49.893
I said, what do you mean, where are the laughs?

38:49.913 --> 38:50.975
He said, it's a drama.

38:50.995 --> 38:52.176
He said, it isn't a comedy.

38:52.814 --> 38:53.775
Jesus Christ.

38:53.815 --> 38:56.678
I said, no, it's a drama.

38:56.698 --> 38:58.780
And he said, but is this the thing we bought for Bette Midler?

39:00.362 --> 39:01.343
Wow.

39:01.363 --> 39:02.083
Never was done.

39:03.265 --> 39:03.885
Never touched.

39:03.905 --> 39:06.047
Did you get paid, right?

39:06.067 --> 39:06.127
No.

39:06.147 --> 39:06.608
You didn't get paid.

39:06.628 --> 39:07.369
No, I was off.

39:07.869 --> 39:08.350
I was out.

39:08.890 --> 39:09.971
Back on the next plane.

39:09.991 --> 39:10.812
You had a nice trip, though.

39:10.832 --> 39:11.433
Yeah, I had a holiday.

39:12.594 --> 39:18.100
But... But you learned that you kind of liked it on that side of the... Hell, yes.

39:18.120 --> 39:19.581
I could move in there.

39:19.780 --> 39:21.703
So when was your first book?

39:21.903 --> 39:23.125
When did you write your first book?

39:24.887 --> 39:32.939
Well, what was odd was after Widows, which was, as I said, a huge success.

39:32.959 --> 39:33.740
On television?

39:33.760 --> 39:35.442
Yeah.

39:35.462 --> 39:45.557
Came seven years of rejection because everybody kept commissioning a script, but basically they wanted another Widows.

39:47.039 --> 39:48.741
And because I wouldn't write another one,

39:49.649 --> 39:51.291
I just got rejected on everything.

39:52.232 --> 39:54.394
So this brings us up to about 1990 then, right?

39:54.994 --> 39:55.235
Yeah.

39:56.856 --> 40:00.660
And midway of that, I was so broke, I was going to go back into acting.

40:00.680 --> 40:02.782
So you've basically taken off in the last five or six years?

40:02.802 --> 40:03.122
Yeah.

40:04.604 --> 40:08.168
And I was approached by somebody and they said, would you like to write a book?

40:08.628 --> 40:15.535
I mean, I was so desperate for money that if they'd said, would you like to write, you know, a book on the football stadium, I'd have said yes.

40:17.056 --> 40:19.639
And so I wrote my first book.

40:19.754 --> 40:24.778
And I love the fact that they commissioned it, I wrote it, they did it.

40:24.798 --> 40:26.560
This was a publisher that came to you?

40:26.580 --> 40:26.840
Yeah.

40:26.860 --> 40:28.302
A British publisher, American?

40:28.882 --> 40:29.843
Pan Macmillan.

40:29.863 --> 40:30.824
And the title was?

40:31.504 --> 40:32.085
The Legacy.

40:32.185 --> 40:33.466
And was it published here?

40:33.586 --> 40:33.786
No.

40:34.187 --> 40:39.211
It was bought by Salmon & Schuster, Michael Corder, and he blocked it.

40:41.433 --> 40:43.635
But then, since then, I've done a book a year.

40:44.416 --> 40:46.157
For Random?

40:46.338 --> 40:49.120
Macmillan in England and Random is my new one here.

40:49.268 --> 40:51.030
I was first with William Morrow.

40:51.070 --> 40:53.313
It's just really come upon hard times.

40:53.734 --> 40:54.975
Yeah, yes.

40:55.056 --> 40:55.676
I think I helped.

40:58.240 --> 41:02.145
But that's how the book started, that I needed them.

41:02.385 --> 41:02.826
I'm sorry.

41:04.087 --> 41:05.830
I'm sorry, I interrupted.

41:05.910 --> 41:07.291
That's how the book started?

41:07.392 --> 41:09.314
Yeah, that I needed them badly.

41:09.434 --> 41:12.518
That you needed them badly.

41:13.039 --> 41:15.462
And everything that you do,

41:16.100 --> 41:19.904
the authenticity, the verisimilitude as to use it.

41:21.106 --> 41:23.028
It goes back to the first time I wrote.

41:23.188 --> 41:25.711
But you really feel that you have to go out and get the real goods.

41:26.391 --> 41:31.857
Yes, because it's a great safety net.

41:31.877 --> 41:36.402
Because if somebody says to me, oh, this is a bit coincidental, isn't it?

41:36.683 --> 41:39.225
I say, pardon?

41:39.245 --> 41:39.726
It's true.

41:40.767 --> 41:46.073
See, you can't slam me for anything

41:46.492 --> 41:47.814
Because I can come back at you.

41:47.834 --> 41:50.298
You can say, listen, I don't think this is well written.

41:50.318 --> 41:51.019
That's my fault.

41:52.521 --> 41:54.865
But to say it didn't happen or it couldn't happen.

41:54.885 --> 41:55.105
Yes.

41:55.666 --> 41:58.150
Is, again, for me, I can turn around and say, aha.

41:59.592 --> 42:03.078
But then, of course, you do have to allow yourself the freedom to imagine.

42:03.098 --> 42:06.503
Oh, I have to sometimes introduce, and that's what I mean.

42:06.543 --> 42:08.426
You can criticize me as a writer.

42:09.708 --> 42:14.676
But, you know, as I say, I always think truth is stranger than fiction.

42:14.842 --> 42:20.428
And the woman who is the model for this book, are you in contact with her?

42:20.448 --> 42:24.111
No, because, I mean, what's odd is by the end of it we hated each other.

42:24.932 --> 42:27.895
She was a very different model.

42:27.915 --> 42:30.798
She also put me in very dangerous situations.

42:30.818 --> 42:32.159
Really?

42:33.180 --> 42:35.583
She used to enjoy it.

42:35.803 --> 42:38.305
So she really is a bitch then, right?

42:38.466 --> 42:39.887
She's a wounded creature.

42:40.238 --> 42:42.582
But a dangerous wounded creature.

42:42.782 --> 42:48.671
She's dangerous, but she is now, I think, I mean, she does have a very good agency, investigating agency.

42:49.653 --> 42:52.317
She is doing very well.

42:53.979 --> 42:55.121
And she's clean.

42:55.522 --> 42:59.768
She hasn't gone back to drink.

43:00.970 --> 43:06.178
But the deal was that I never, ever said where she came from, what station she was

43:06.597 --> 43:09.602
But people must know who she is.

43:09.622 --> 43:12.147
It would be hard to find her.

43:13.389 --> 43:15.052
Very hard to find her.

43:15.092 --> 43:17.417
People in the PD must know who she is, no?

43:18.098 --> 43:19.921
Yeah.

43:20.482 --> 43:21.244
For what it's worth.

43:21.624 --> 43:23.067
Yeah.

43:24.329 --> 43:26.513
But they think she's lower than the

43:26.763 --> 43:28.586
But she came basically with money?

43:28.626 --> 43:29.487
Yes.

43:29.547 --> 43:31.850
The first time she came to me, she needed money badly.

43:32.111 --> 43:35.075
And there's no satisfaction in seeing the story?

43:35.656 --> 43:47.493
No, because, you know, you weave in her story, and then I have to weave out of it stuff that she can say can be directly linked to her, that she can be picked out.

43:48.575 --> 43:53.462
And she didn't like the fact that she felt I softened her.

43:55.366 --> 44:00.633
But, of course, the plot, the serial killer thing, that's totally invention.

44:00.653 --> 44:00.914
No.

44:01.795 --> 44:05.139
There was a serial killer, the hammer killer.

44:05.159 --> 44:08.223
He used the claw hammer in identically the same way.

44:08.464 --> 44:10.246
But not involved with her in any way.

44:10.867 --> 44:11.087
No.

44:11.147 --> 44:18.738
The murder that she actually witnessed that drew her back into police work was a random killing in the street.

44:19.639 --> 44:21.341
So she found that murder for me.

44:22.282 --> 44:22.723
I said, well...

44:22.855 --> 44:30.706
If you don't want me to put that because it identifies you and your location, bring me the murder that I can use in this.

44:31.527 --> 44:38.236
And so she brought me the prostitute that had been scarred on the back of her head.

44:39.258 --> 44:40.820
Well, I paid her for it.

44:42.142 --> 44:51.495
But what was so odd was that the day she called me up and she said, I think I've got the case for you.

44:51.982 --> 44:56.148
And we're in a cafe outside in Beverly Hills on Rodeo Drive.

44:57.670 --> 45:01.175
And she's got this hookah with her that she's brought in.

45:01.215 --> 45:04.499
I mean, she was always bringing me expenses.

45:04.519 --> 45:06.482
You know, they came in from here, there and everywhere.

45:07.103 --> 45:07.904
Plane tickets.

45:07.984 --> 45:10.868
I mean, I don't know where she got half these expenses from.

45:10.888 --> 45:12.470
But anyway, she got this girl with her.

45:15.134 --> 45:18.258
I mean, she did not... I was weeping with laughter.

45:18.699 --> 45:19.660
She made me laugh too much.

45:20.568 --> 45:24.755
But she was the prostitute involved in the murder.

45:25.256 --> 45:29.523
And they got very loud.

45:30.424 --> 45:31.907
We're out on the pavement.

45:31.927 --> 45:36.514
And there's a little woman sitting within a foot of us.

45:36.534 --> 45:44.928
So they said, anyway, and the Lorraine says, go on, tell her, you've got to give all the details, because if you don't get the details, she keeps on coming back.

45:45.028 --> 45:47.192
Go on, tell her the details, tell her the details.

45:47.212 --> 45:47.352
See?

45:47.635 --> 45:50.678
As the girl's telling me the details, she keeps interrupting.

45:51.119 --> 45:53.261
She's given a blowjob, right?

45:53.341 --> 45:55.444
She's given the blowjob.

45:56.926 --> 45:59.929
And there's this woman on this table going, just look.

46:01.871 --> 46:07.157
So what Lorraine was saying was to position the girl.

46:07.598 --> 46:11.863
He's in the driving seat and she's in the passenger seat.

46:12.043 --> 46:14.065
So the head's going down to do the business.

46:15.074 --> 46:27.071
And then he clamped her with his right hand and then opened the glove compartment with his left, which meant that he was a left-handed, coming with the hammer with the left hand.

46:27.091 --> 46:28.253
Not necessarily, though.

46:28.273 --> 46:30.396
Oh, sure, if he had to go over with that hand, sure.

46:30.416 --> 46:31.858
Yes, you can't whack with that.

46:31.898 --> 46:38.007
So if he's got a head there, you've got to have a pretty good... And he went down with the hammer, twist it, and then pull the claw.

46:38.027 --> 46:41.211
So they virtually had their scalps ripped off.

46:42.353 --> 46:42.994
Jesus Christ.

46:43.014 --> 46:43.815
And...

46:45.415 --> 46:55.529
And so we had that serial killer, so I could not put just that serial killer, because then I could be sued by his family.

46:56.530 --> 47:06.263
I've now got to find yet another crime to lap on top of that, which was the second one she came up with was the high society family.

47:06.283 --> 47:08.526
You must keep some lawyers busy.

47:08.546 --> 47:10.549
I have one in permanent pay.

47:11.571 --> 47:12.672
In permanent pay.

47:12.888 --> 47:19.740
As they check through, they go, oh, my God.

47:20.221 --> 47:28.615
We had one chapter of my book that had to be read, line for line, and we got this guy up here threatening us with a mid-$15 million suit.

47:28.635 --> 47:29.457
It's a great story.

47:29.497 --> 47:31.921
I mean, this guy's a total fabrication.

47:31.961 --> 47:34.305
Anyway, I should send you a copy of my book.

47:34.994 --> 47:35.977
Oh, I'd love it.

47:36.097 --> 47:39.226
I think I've got plenty of stuff, and I've got a 10.30, so I'm going to... Okay.

47:39.407 --> 47:40.751
I wonder if you'd inscribe this for me.

47:41.072 --> 47:41.333
Yes.

47:41.894 --> 47:43.439
If you'd like, give me your P.O.

47:43.479 --> 47:43.840
box.

